# Decide Claude auto-memory

## Step

Claude Code's auto-memory (`~/.claude/projects/-Users-joel/memory/`) is a
live shadow source: it duplicates operator truths that belong in the
Brain, and it wrote a fresh topic page on 07-17 after Joel's 07-16
Brain-only instruction. Settle: disable topic-page writes entirely, or
reshape the surface into a read-only index pointing at Brain pages —
and either way, what happens to the 18 existing topic pages (migrate the
non-duplicated facts into Brain `.svx`, then delete?). The answer must
bind future Claude sessions mechanically (instruction text where the
memory feature reads it), not aspirationally. Evidence:
[periphery survey](../memory-system-review/periphery-survey.svx)
"Claude auto-memory".

## Decision (Joel, 2026-07-17, grilled live)

**Pointer index.** Auto-memory stops being a content store and becomes a
map into the Brain:

1. Migrate the non-duplicated facts from the 18 topic pages into Brain
   `.svx` notes, then delete the topic pages.
2. Rewrite `MEMORY.md` as: (a) a binding rule at the top — no new topic
   pages, durable facts go to Brain `.svx`, only pointers live here —
   and (b) one-line pointers to the relevant Brain pages below.
3. The rule binds mechanically because `MEMORY.md` is loaded into every
   Claude session's context; that's the one surface the memory feature
   is guaranteed to read before writing.

Rationale: the index loads for free every session — useful recall real
estate. Kill-without-pointers makes sessions blinder for no gain; the
migration is identical either way.
